   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1841-02_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#North-Audley-Street-1_ENK">N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. 1 North Audley <choice>
                        <orig>Str</orig>
                        <reg>Street</reg>
                     </choice>
                  </placeName>
                  <date when="1841-02-28">28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. February 1841</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HallX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hall</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>While my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">sister</persName> on her<lb/>
               sofa is crying out as she<lb/>
               turns over your pages<lb/>
               Your writings &amp; your<lb/>
               drawings<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               "How pretty! How good!<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I write as fast as pen<lb/>
               can go and faster than it<lb/>
               ought to go, (<unclear>as</unclear> your messenger <unclear/>
               <lb/>
               to thank you for your <choice>
                  <orig>indefati<lb/>
               gable</orig>
                  <reg>indefatigable</reg>
               </choice> goodness to me -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Your fifth number I am<lb/>
               sure from what you say and<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is saying will be<lb/>
               surpassing! Lest I omit<lb/>
               what concerns me so much<lb/>
               let me this in<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. answer<lb/>
               your kind question &amp; say<lb/>
               that whatever at any time of<lb/>
               these numbers (or whatever you<lb/>
               please) to my sister <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Lestock<lb/>
               Wilson</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1841-02_page02.jpg"/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#North-Audley-Street-1_ENK">1 North Audley Street</placeName> she will<lb/>
               forward it to me at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths<lb/>
               town</placeName> - Where I shall be<lb/>
               Alas too soon &amp; about the<lb/>
               7<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. certainly I leave <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName>
               <lb/>
               But if it be possible for me<lb/>
               to get out to pay my thanks<lb/>
               &amp; adieus to you in the course<lb/>
               of next week I will do so<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               and if I really cannot<lb/>
               You must &amp; you will my<lb/>
               dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HallX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hall</persName> take the good will<lb/>
               for the ill deed -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I am sincerely sorry you<lb/>
               have been ill - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">my sister</persName>
               <lb/>
               is a great deal better and I<lb/>
               trust that under <persName ref="./Personography.xml#AshbX1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Ashburners</persName>
               <lb/>
               care she will get through well<lb/>
               and be blessed with the long<lb/>
               delayed &amp; therefore more<lb/>
               precious blessing - most precious<lb/>
               blessing of happy marriage<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1841-02_page03.jpg"/>
               - She desires to be kindly<lb/>
               remembered to you<lb/>
               and joins with me in<lb/>
               entreating you to stop in<lb/>
               time and not to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">
                  <hi rend="underline">Walter-Scott</hi>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
               yourself by over exertion<lb/>
               You should consider that<lb/>
               you lose time for ever <unclear>
                  <del/>
               </unclear>
               <lb/>
               power for ever if you lose<lb/>
               health - And that no <choice>
                  <orig>mo=<lb/>
               =ney</orig>
                  <reg>money</reg>
               </choice> can repurchase it for<lb/>
               you or give you back the<lb/>
               power of writing as now<lb/>
               you do - creating whatever<lb/>
               by that magic touch<lb/>
               you wish or want<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Take advice &amp; take warn<lb/>
               ing &amp; take notice that<lb/>
               good warning is better than<lb/>
               good advice - even medical<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               - I am my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HallX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Hall</persName>
               <lb/>
               Yours sincerely<lb/>
               Perhaps impertinently<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
         </div>
